Some people think that competition at work, at school and in daily life is a good thing. Others believe that we should try to cooperate more, rather than competing against each other.

Discuss both these views and give your own opinion.

While there is no denying that competition is regarded by many as a panacea to boost efficiency in multiple aspects of social life, there are also those who argue that cooperation should be the primary mode of operation when it comes to conducting human affairs. One may easily find truth to both of these views.

The notion that competition delivers good results is fairly ancient and intuitive. In the work place, for example, a healthy rivalry among employees as well as departments translates to added efforts to "pull one's weight", resulting in maximum productivity for the company. In schools, students compete for academic excellence, each bent on beating the other in study hours and high grades; as a result everybody learns much more effectively. In general, competition serves as a catalyst in our daily life, helping to bring forth the best potential out of every individual.

On the other hand, the intuition of cooperation is equally old and indispensable. Just think of a mammoth hunt back when we were hunter-gatherers, where the survival of our race depended on teamwork and trust. The spirit of cooperation manifests itself everywhere: be it in the basketball court, during a rescue scenario in the aftermath of an earthquake, or more mundanely in a central kitchen where everyone must work in tandem with the team. It's not an exaggeration to say that cooperation is in our DNA.

However, both competition and cooperation can be counter productive if carried to the extreme. Excess competition may lead to high pressure and ill-will among individuals, sometimes to a point where cooperation is impossible, ultimately hurting production. By the same token, too much cooperation may give rise to a tolerance of impotence or even nepotism. Therefore, I believe it is important to strike a right balance between the two, so that the value of both would be maximized.



These days, alternative medicines have become a controversial issue often spurring public debate. In my view, the efficacy of these so called alternatives are questionable at best. In fact, they are more often than not just snake oil, in one form or another.

There is no denying that these nostrums have attracted quite a large following, in part due to their ancient roots in some cases going back to antiquity. Spread far and wide thanks to recent advancements such as social media, they seem especially appealing to those who are either desperate in their condition or rather credulous to anecdotes. For example, some people diagnosed with cancer prefer Chinese Traditional Medicine to standard treatments, believing in CTM's inexplicable power over the cancerous cells -- a conviction solely based on hearsay, that such and such has healed from the same cancer in less than a year just by taking CTM. These people have never heard of the Double Blind Test, or taken the time to ask themselves the simple question: if boiled leaves or holy cow's urine are the answer, why have they not become the mainstream already, and made a few Nobel prize winners along the way?
